revision.text:
{{hatnote|This page is about the various taxonomic groupings of related organisms; it should not be confused with the ecological grouping of unrelated plant taxa in [[phytosociology]].}}
An '''alliance''' is an [[informal group (taxonomy)|informal grouping]] used in [[Taxonomy (biology)|biological taxonomy]]. The term "alliance" is not a [[taxonomic rank]] defined in any of the [[nomenclature codes]]. It is used for any group of [[species]],<ref>{{citation |author=Emshwiller, E. |date=2002 |title=Ploidy Levels among Species in the ‘Oxalis tuberosa Alliance’ as Inferred by Flow Cytometry |journal=Annals of Botany |volume=89 |issue=6 |pages=741–753 |url=http://aob.oxfordjournals.org/content/89/6/741.abstract |doi=10.1093/aob/mcf135|pmc=4233841 }}</ref> [[genus|genera]]<ref>{{citation |display-authors=6 |author=Zhai, J.-W. |author2=Zhang, G.-Q. |author3=Li, L. |author4=Wang, M. |author5=Chen, L.-J. |author6=Chung, S.-W. |author7=Rodríguez, F.J. |author8=Francisco-Ortega, J. |author9=Lan, S.-R. |author10=Xing, F.-W. |author11=Liu, Z.-J. |author12=Zhai, J.W. |author13=Zhang, G.Q. |author14=Li, L. |author15=Wang, M. |author16=Chen, L.J. |author17=Chung, S.W. |author18=Rodriguez, F.J. |author19=Francisco-Ortega, J. |author20=Lan, S.R. |author21=Xing, F.W. |author22=Liu, Z.J. |date=2014 |title=A new phylogenetic analysis sheds new light on the relationships in the Calanthe alliance (Orchidaceae) in China |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=77 |issue=Complete |pages=216–222 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2014.04.005 |pmid=24747128}}</ref> or [[tribe (biology)|tribes]] to which authors wish to refer, that have at some time provisionally been considered to be closely related.

The term is often used for a group that authors are studying in further detail in order to refine the complex taxonomy. For example, a [[molecular phylogenetics]] study of the Aerides–Vanda Alliance (Orchidaceae: Epidendroideae) confirmed that the group is [[monophyly|monophyletic]], and clarified which species belong in each of the 14 genera.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Zhang Guo-Qiang, Liu Ke-Wei, Chen Li-Jun, Xiao Xin-Ju, Zhai Jun-Wen, Li Li-Qiang, Cai Jing, Hsiao Yu-Yun, Rao Wen-Hui, Huang Jie, Ma Xue-Yong, Chung Shih-Wen, Huang Lai-Qiang, Tsai Wen-Chieh, Liu Zhong-Jian | year = 2013| title = ''A New Molecular Phylogeny and a New Genus, Pendulorchis, of the Aerides–Vanda Alliance (Orchidaceae: Epidendroideae)'' | url = | journal = PLOS One | volume = 8| issue = 4| page = e60097| doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0060097 }}</ref> In other orchid groups, the various alliances that have been defined do not correspond well to [[clade]]s.<ref>{{citation |author=Salazar, G.A. |author2=Chase, M.W. |author3=Soto Arenas, M.A. |author4=Ingrouille, M. |date=2003 |title=Phylogenetics of Cranichideae with emphasis on Spiranthinae (Orchidaceae, Orchidoideae): evidence from plastid and nuclear DNA sequences |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=90 |issue=5 |pages=777–795 |url=http://www.amjbot.org/content/90/5/777.abstract |doi=10.3732/ajb.90.5.777 |pmid=21659175}}</ref>

Historically, some 19th century botanical authors used alliance to denote groups that would now be considered [[Order (biology)|orders]]. This usage is now obsolete, and the [[International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants|ICN]] (Article 17.2) specifies that such taxa are treated as orders.

